It has been two years since I've been doing YWA. This is my fourth 30 day journey and this session was by far my least favorite; not because it was challenging, but because it was too reminiscent of everything I hate about "working out" in the traditional sense. I grew to appreciate yoga and commit to a regular practice because of YWA. The idea of showing up for myself and exploring what my body is capable of doing really resonated with me, more than pushing my body to its limits in pursuit of some external ideal of what it should look like. This session erred too much on the side of the latter and left me  feeling sad and defeated. I felt there was a huge disjuncture between this core session and the others I've done in the past.....not sure I'll continue with this challenge.

WORD OF CAUTION TO NON ABLE BODIED PEOPLES:  this MOVE series thus far has very fast pace with no initial suggestion or option for alternate positions or props until you are a few breaths deep into the pose.  which can be extremely dangerous to transition out of unless at an advanced level of yoga, or able bodied.   for anyone who is apart of the fat community or anyone who struggles with an older injury and atrophied muscles, I do NOT recommend this series.  this series, while well intended, has the potential to interrupt and inflame old injuries due to the lack of inclusivity and consideration.  I do love yoga w/adriene, however I am used to her addressing the optional props needed as well as the optional pose levels either before the yoga gets started or before we go into a pose.

I've learned a lot from doing these iconic day 6 practices over the years. I always struggle with bicycles and other core work done lying down because I tend to compensate with my back. Recently, though, I've realized that making the effort to do the movement correctly and safely, taking breaks when I need to, and coming back when I feel ready is a entirely different type of core work. It involves returning to my inner self and taking care of my body and mind first, so that the physical work I do on the mat can serve me better. I've learned to be kinder to myself and listen to my gut, even if it means I don't get in quite as many reps, and I think that's the best kind of core work.

Yoga shouldn't leave you frustrated and hurt: it should leave you with a clear mind and new perspective, it should provide modifications and adjust to your body. Yes, it can be difficult but not frustrating. This here for me isn't yoga, it's workout. I came to practice yoga, not to jump into a workout without proper stretching and warmup beforehand. I never feel angry and frustrated after a practice, in spite of all struggles and difficulties I still manage to find peace but not with this "practice". I will  leave this yoga challenge and I think that's a shame: it should have been a nurturing moment, but this looks to be done just for the views and sake of it.

To all the beginners out there trying this: if you're struggling and think you can't do it or you're not fit for it, that's not it. This practice isn't suitable for beginners, instructions are not clear as they should be (I struggled a lot with the obliques work and I'm not a beginner). Be careful, don't hurt yourself and be sure to stretch properly before and after the practice. If you're doubting yourself, it's not you. It's this practice in particular that isn't suitable for you. Try to look up for Yoga With Kassandra. Her instructions are crystal clear and following them you won't get hurt and still get results.

I just wanted to comment for anyone (like me!) who has to be mindful of the pressure they put on their pelvic floor - any floor ab work where both your legs are off the ground and moving simultaneously can be very tough on the PF, and not ideal if you have any kind of pelvic prolapse (similar with plank poses of any kind) Take time to engage your full core from your pelvic floor up, and if it's hard to maintain that connection its much safer to modify the moves (I often take a plank to my knees or swap floor ab work for standing moves). I'm speaking purely from my own experience and research here, after 2 kids and a long journey reconnecting with what my post-pregnancy body needs to be strong and healthy!

Thank you, Adriene, for making these challenges and yoga videos for almost a decade now, and helping me learn to love my own movement for over five years. Your channel is truly a blessing.

However, this practice felt off - I'm not a huge fan of Day 6, but usually it's because I'm frustrated with my own core strength, not because the practice is difficult to follow or doesn't feel like yoga. Some of the transitions were poorly narrated (e.g., moving from the hip lifts to cobbler's pose and back again), several of the movements were very heavy on the shoulders, with barely any warm-up, and the end was just an aerobics class - straight up crunches. This was disappointing, mostly because it didn't feel like it was in line with your many previous takes on yogic core work and there wasn't much of a flow to it. All in all, I'm sorry to say that this practice left me feeling frazzled and sort of like it wasn't a complete practice at all.

Here's hoping it's just a fluke, though, because the rest of the challenge so far has been excellent!

I'm not going to lie, I took a look at today's practice and felt instantly discouraged. I loved day 5 because it incorporated some pigeon pose and yogic squat, but I've really struggled with all the sessions so far. I'm not a total beginner, but this is my first time back to the mat in a couple of years and my body and abilities are different than they were before. That said, I didn't let my feelings stop me from getting on the mat today. I chose to do a different hip-opening episode of about the same length of time to help strengthen and stretch out my hips, which is one of my weak points at the moment. Then I did some independent shoulder stretches and lower-back-strengthening poses. So when I'm back tomorrow for day 7, I'll be stretched refreshed! If there's anyone else who needs to hear this today, this is for you: don't feel discouraged--take it at your pace. You know your body better than anyone else. The fact that you're on the mat is a huge win, whether you finished this session, did some of it, or did something else! Be as gentle with your mind as you are with your body. Do what's right for you. It will make sessions like today's all the more possible to conquer in the future. <3

My body has changed a lot in the past year since Breath. There are things I remember doing last year that I simply cannot do anymore. And yet during the practice I found myself being grateful for my body and how it is now, that I can move it and that it supports me, albeit in different and sometimes more painful ways than previously. And I felt grateful to myself, for knowing it would be hard and deciding to show up for myself anyway. It felt so good to reach the end of practice and tell myself I love myself. And I have a lot of that love because of yoga and because of your guidance, Adriene. Thank you for shining a light on the path to self-love and self-acceptance so I could walk down it with more ease and gratitude. And thank you to everyone for sharing your practice with me, not just now but every day of the year. Thank you. üôè

I used to do Yoga daily especially when the pandemic started back in 2020. I started with a video from one of Adriene‚Äôs 30-day challenges, then eventually I developed my own personal practice and managed to do it for a more than a year. But then I got really sick last year and skipped a couple of days, so the daily yoga practice turned into twice a week, to once a month to eventually none again. I could blame it on getting sick, or just being busy with life or just physical and mental exhaustion from working as a nurse, but truth is, I just lost my motivation. There are mornings when I‚Äôm wide awake just in bed scrolling mindlessly on social media or watching random videos on Youtube refusing to move until I have to prepare to go to work again. 

Funnily enough the new year started and as I opened Youtube it was Adriene‚Äôs video that popped up first-an invitation for another 30days of Yoga. 

I‚Äôm still busy (struggling to cope up) with life, still exhausted from work, but for the past few days since that video, I just push myself to show up again, everyday, as an act of self care. And I‚Äôll keep trying with you all for the rest of the days. üíï

I used to get frustrated and even angry when my body wouldn't do all of the exercises that I wanted it to do. I've since cultivated a better relationship with myself, and now when my muscles start to tremble or even when I collapse out of a pose, I just laugh. Needless to say, there was a lot of laughter during this practice. But I was also surprised by how much I was able to do. So overall, this practice was awesome and just what I needed today!

One of my largest personal growth moments has been holding my emotions and not running away with them, particularly the negative ones. I don‚Äôt know why, or what it is about this specific day of practice (I‚Äôve done at least 1 full 30 day journey with Adriene before and countless other videos regularly), but the most ignited thing for me was my anger. Something about this practice being today‚Äôs journey was just not vibing with me, and quickly got me frustrated. My elbows hurt a lot during the side lifts, it felt like I was looking for the relaxing and the calming parts of yoga and today kept hitting the part of a practice I normally avoid. At multiple points, I let out an angry and frustrated ‚ÄúAdriene!!‚Äù while getting into yet another core flexing pose. But what I realized by the end of it was that instead of what historically would be pausing the video and giving up, or switching to a different practice, I actually stepped up to modify and support myself with my needs of the day. I let myself yell and groan through the hard parts. I folded my mat over to cushion but kept with the side lifts. I took breaks when I wanted to give up, but always rejoined the pose for the final moments or movements, even when I wanted to scream (often while letting out at least a little one). The most loving thing I did for myself, which upon reflection made me cry and drove me to write a comment on one of your videos for the first time in years of joining your practice, was telling myself that I‚Äôm not giving up on you, and you‚Äôre worth it. Loving yourself is easy when the work is easy, but showing unconditional love even when faced with frustration and challenges and what feels like meeting limitations is a lesson i‚Äôll be holding deeply close to my heart for a long time ‚ù§Ô∏è
